Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B ,
Happy Thursday! We=E2=80=99re back with the second installment of The Found=
er=E2=80=99s Letter.=20
Inspired by the letter [https://substack.com/redirect/5e757056-c0fd-49eb-8e=
7d-ef9cd330a290?u=3D16283549] Kevin Song [https://substack.com/redirect/090=
dfec3-4edf-4968-9534-200f5ef86569?u=3D16283549] wrote to announce his compa=
ny, withco [https://substack.com/redirect/d4ba65e8-3820-415c-9088-bb56f62b2=
868?u=3D16283549], every month, we=E2=80=99re going to turn the keyboard ov=
er to a founder in the Not Boring Capital portfolio to tell their story in =
their words.=20
Today, Jordan Singer [https://substack.com/redirect/9e8169b4-b553-496f-b4b9=
-d46933023b80?u=3D16283549] is going to tell you about his lifelong passion=
 for design and code, and how he=E2=80=99s combining them in his new compan=
y: Diagram [https://substack.com/redirect/1f79368a-350f-4440-844f-fbc444837=
188?u=3D16283549].=20
I first came across Jordan, like so many people did, on Twitter. In the mid=
st of the COVID lockdown, Jordan, an ex-Square designer, started building w=
himsical apps in public, sharing his process as he went. I think the first =
one I saw was Airport [https://substack.com/redirect/f435ef09-15da-48e7-910=
e-09b8807009f5?u=3D16283549], which let people discover TestFlight apps for=
 that moment in time when getting access to the TestFlight was the thing in=
 our corner of the internet.=20
Then he built a series of simple, lil apps like lil wallet [https://substac=
k.com/redirect/fb3ecdf4-8a57-43ea-b8ef-7ecae982c63b?u=3D16283549], lil weat=
her [https://substack.com/redirect/9f4a8bd9-390c-49dc-9268-01491b6bcaaf?u=
=3D16283549], lil OS [https://substack.com/redirect/a4e71350-0019-46a6-94bc=
-bfe05f09749d?u=3D16283549], and a dozen more. By the time he publicly laun=
ched Diagram and announced a $3 million Seed round [https://substack.com/re=
direct/a9be468b-bd7d-45ab-9dcc-f125d5c80078?u=3D16283549] in May, he=E2=80=
=99d built up a following of over 50k people attracted to watching him crea=
te.=20
Diagram makes design tools, many built on top of Figma. If you=E2=80=99re f=
amiliar with what GitHub=E2=80=99s Copilot does for coders =E2=80=94 uses A=
I to help them write better code, faster =E2=80=94 Diagram wants to do the =
same for designers.=20
Diagram makes designers=E2=80=99 lives easier and gives them superpowers. U=
ltimately, it will let anyone (even a terrible designer like me) design lik=
e a pro. To me, it seems like a philosophical sibling to Replit [https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/19acd939-3c48-4587-8185-1bd668b643ba?u=3D16283549]; bot=
h help more people create the internet they want to use. When it=E2=80=99s =
successful, Diagram will make the internet a more beautiful, magical, creat=
ive place.=20
Over to Jordan.=20
The Founder=E2=80=99s Letter: Jordan Singer, Diagram
Browsing the internet in the early 2000s was a boring, predictable experien=
ce. Met with Times New Roman fonts and dark blue hyperlinks, every site loo=
ked mostly the same. If your Wayback Machine [https://substack.com/redirect=
/432f5cb7-892e-4747-b69d-4ab53c4f10fa?u=3D16283549] is broken, here are a f=
ew examples of nostalgic sites like MySpace and Wikipedia:
The only sites that stood out used different fonts, more colors, and vibran=
t imagery. I recall a 2004 version of apple.com that instantly captivated m=
e. It was simple, easy to navigate, and almost artisanal in its craftsmansh=
ip. Intrigued, I wanted to know how to make a website like that for myself,=
 but first I needed to learn how they were built.
The eMachines PC of my childhood bedroom served as a portal=E2=80=94albeit =
a rather slow, noisy one=E2=80=94into an entirely new world. At a young age=
, this portal introduced me to a very important idea: the software that I w=
as using, the internet I was browsing, was built by other people. If they c=
ould do it, why couldn=E2=80=99t I?
This led to my discovery of code. I started to learn code by inspecting the=
 source code of my favorite websites. Like any good artist, I first copied =
existing sites. I would adjust the text, change some colors, and move both =
blocks and elements around. It felt magical that you could write some struc=
tured text that a web browser could understand.
Unfortunately, my sites were a visual mess, and I began to realize that cod=
e was only part of the equation. The sites from which I took inspiration, l=
ike apple.com, were also thoughtfully designed with intention. Someone deci=
ded where things were positioned and how they appeared. Thus began my foray=
 into design. I started to understand the relationships between different e=
lements by inspecting other sites=E2=80=99 use of size, color, and position=
=2E I learned to design by working backwa=
rds from code, and=E2=80=94through l=
ots of trial and error =E2=80=94I started to discover my passion for buildi=
ng things.
For as long as I can remember, I have been building, whether by hand at a y=
oung age playing with LEGOs or by keyboard=E2=80=94writing code to create s=
oftware. The possibilities are infinite when your personal creations can sh=
ape your world. Back then, I built things to solve my own problems and chil=
dlike curiosities. If useful to me, I would build it for myself and share i=
t with the world. A few of my earliest products from my middle school days =
in 2009 were a simple way to check the forecast in any location called Weat=
hr and a site for viewing nearby theater showtimes called NowShowing.
Building to solve my own problems proved far more relatable than building f=
or someone else. I understood the pressing urge or need for something to ex=
ist and so, I built it how I would want it to work. When you build things f=
or yourself, you understand the problem better and can empathize with build=
ing for them more deeply.
In 2017, I landed at Square [https://substack.com/redirect/bec14247-32d6-4c=
8d-a165-7d97a4a8058e?u=3D16283549], a company I admired for its sleek desig=
n aesthetic. There, I worked on the Cash App as a product designer. It was =
a brand new experience for me, working alongside a design team and focusing=
 solely on design. I started to empathize with and understand the problems =
and needs of the designers that make up larger design teams. There are all =
sorts of tedious, cumbersome, repetitive tasks that designers do everyday, =
from manually maintaining design systems with hundreds of components to org=
anizing large and messy files. And, when I found myself or others doing tho=
se things, I saw the chance for automation to make life easier. Just like b=
efore, my desire to solve my own problems created the opportunity to build;=
 and so building for designers meant building design tools. I realized that=
 by building for myself, I could build for others and solve their problems =
too.
While at Square, I started to miss coding because I was so focused on desig=
n. During the pandemic summer of 2020, I used my extra time at home to get =
back to building. One of the projects I explored was called lil software [h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/b1b1dfe3-a764-43a6-86dd-aa0a81aa5694?u=3D16283=
549]. The entire idea was to make =E2=80=9Clil apps=E2=80=9D that took exis=
ting utility-based apps like Weather or Calculator and make a lil version o=
f them=E2=80=94simple and minimal, with just enough functionality to get by=
=2E It was my excuse to learn how to make=
 iOS apps. I started sharing these l=
il apps on Twitter and began hitting my stride by building an audience of t=
hose interested in both design and code. I created a brand behind all that =
I built called I build my ideas [https://substack.com/redirect/eafe9d10-be1=
5-4099-b962-f8c03461fff6?u=3D16283549] and went on to experiment with proje=
cts like Airport [https://substack.com/redirect/1cf12475-a057-4856-b1ad-e2a=
86d8eba6a?u=3D16283549], which created a way to discover TestFlight apps, a=
nd Figma plugins like Designer [https://substack.com/redirect/0940e9ec-7d82=
-4a7f-b68d-d9ca73100b40?u=3D16283549], which used AI to design for you via =
a simple description.
All of these projects and experiences have led to founding Diagram [https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/52d01c0c-ca27-41f2-8243-a09b5d2bc5dc?u=3D16283549].=20
At Diagram, we are exploring the untapped intersection of product design an=
d AI. We=E2=80=99ve seen the impact of AI on everything from copywriting [h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/03cc00d9-d82d-4a7d-8339-0fcda1116a35?u=3D16283=
549] to video editing [https://substack.com/redirect/f56570b7-c74e-440a-a7b=
f-44f3f6082204?u=3D16283549] to coding [https://substack.com/redirect/74b1f=
856-0fea-4ad9-919a-8469a7ac17ff?u=3D16283549], and we plan to put AI to wor=
k accelerating both designers and their workflows. Our first product, Autom=
ator [https://substack.com/redirect/bc197688-b593-47f2-a396-795481649482?u=
=3D16283549], automates Figma design tasks like importing external data and=
 outlining your design specs in one click without any code. We have designe=
rs and design teams of all shapes and sizes automating the things they do i=
n Figma day to day and saving them hours of time each week. They love that =
it removes the need to spend lots of manual time=E2=80=94via many points an=
d clicks=E2=80=94and frees them up to focus on being more creative. One des=
ign team uses an automation every time they need to duplicate a template fi=
le tailored for each of their new projects, saving them hours of work. An a=
mazing community has grown all around it and we=E2=80=99re only just at the=
 start.
In addition to Automator, we=E2=80=99re actively working on building a larg=
er suite of AI design tools. An upcoming Figma plugin of ours called Magici=
an [https://substack.com/redirect/aa91bee9-6db3-4b40-a1bc-21c907583cd9?u=3D=
16283549] will be our first experiment to introduce AI into the design tool=
 as a companion that helps with design tasks like automatically renaming yo=
ur layers for you. It=E2=80=99s going to be an experimental playground to l=
earn from and gather feedback that we=E2=80=99ll apply to the tools we buil=
d in the future.
When you have an idea for an app or website, staring at a blank canvas and =
not knowing how to visualize what you have in your head can be scary for th=
ose that don=E2=80=99t know how to design. One day, design will be so acces=
sible that anyone will be able to visualize their ideas with low effort and=
 design the software they=E2=80=99re using and the internet they=E2=80=99re=
 browsing. At Diagram [https://substack.com/redirect/52d01c0c-ca27-41f2-824=
3-a09b5d2bc5dc?u=3D16283549], we=E2=80=99re building magical new ways to de=
sign products that make design accessible to everyone.=20
A childlike curiosity has continued to stick with me. It's the thing that k=
eeps me building towards bringing out the inner creative and designer in ea=
ch of us. If you want to play a big role on our small team and help build t=
he future of design, we=E2=80=99re hiring [https://substack.com/redirect/9e=
11ac69-6e7c-4f44-ac22-68f02560c76c?u=3D16283549].
Keep on building,
Jordan
Thanks to Jordan [https://substack.com/redirect/9e8169b4-b553-496f-b4b9-d46=
933023b80?u=3D16283549] for writing his Founder=E2=80=99s Letter, and to To=
m [https://substack.com/redirect/fe61d4be-e3f4-4c00-81ee-90b75aba3d95?u=3D1=
6283549] and Dan [https://substack.com/redirect/e602d482-684a-4400-97d0-e7d=
bfc47f4bf?u=3D16283549] for editing!
Programming note: we=E2=80=99ll be sending next week=E2=80=99s newsletter o=
n Tuesday because of the 4th of July holiday. Happy 4th =F0=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=
=87=B8
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

